##     colsplit, melt, recast
setwd("~/Downloads")
df <- read.csv("arthritis-data.csv", as.is=TRUE)
#Convert wide-formatted data into long

data <- reshape(df, varying=c("Baseline","Month2", "Month4", "Month6"), 
               v.names = "ACS",
                timevar = "Month", 
               times =c(0,2,4,6),
              direction = "long")
data = data[!is.na(data$ACS), ]
for(i in 1:nrow(data)){
  if(data$ACS[i] == 1 | data$ACS[i] == 2){
    data$outcome[i] = 1
  }else if(data$ACS[i] == 3){
    data$outcome[i] = 2
  }else if(data$ACS[i] == 4 | data$ACS[i] == 5){
     data$outcome[i] = 3
  }
}

In month0 for the treatment and drug group, the proportion seems very similar, and the proportion of ACS in range 1 is 0.25, proportion of ACS in range 2 is 0.45, proportion of ACS in range 2 is 0.3 approximately.

In month2, in the drug group. The proportion of of ACS in range 1 increases to 0.3, while the proportion of of ACS in range 2 decreases to 0.38. In the drug group, the the proportion of of ACS in range 2 increases to 0.5 approximately.

while in month4 and month6, in the drug groups compared with the placebo groups, the proportion of the ACS in range 1 all increase. which means the drug do have the effect in decrease the level of ACS.

Interpret random effect: for every squaremonth unit change in Xijk , the log-odds of a cumulative response patients’ difference change probability will change by β for an individual with propensity to respond ‘higher or lower’ (depending on whether lower or higher values are modeled) equal to bi .

According to the slides, “Proportionality Assumption: if a unit increase in a covariate doubles the odds of being in Yi=1 vs. Yi>1, it also doubles the odds of being in Yi≤2 vs. Yi>2, etc” And we can tell from the plot: that The slope of change in the cumulative log-odds for and the log-odds are increasing proportionally across different cumulative logits, and the ratios remain constant, which obeys the Proportionality Assumption.

Interpret the estimated odds ratio at 4 months of follow up: since at month 4, the odds ratio is 0.5159536. which means the proportion of the treatment and placebo group has a ratio of 0.5159536. which means the treatment group will have 51% probability to have a worse outcome.

    1. From the textbook, the estimates of the trt:sqrtmonth is 0.4005. which are different from the m1, Trt:squaremonth -0.33087. The reason why they are different: because the book use the different calculatuion method, with different principle, so they are different.

#3a i

Let Yij ={1,2,3…n} for the ith patient self-reporting scale value in the jth occasion (j=0 [baseline],2 [2mo], 4 [4 mo], 6 [6 mo]).

logit{E(Yij=c|bi(c))} = log{ Pr (Yij= c|bi(c)) / Pr (Yij =C|bi(c)) } =
= β1(c) + β2(c)Trti + β3(c)sqrt(Timeij) + β4(c)Trti x sqrt(Timeij)+ b1i(c)

Since the p value is 0.06963 > 0.05 so this means we cannot reject the H0, so at least for beta4 Treatment:squaremonth, beta41 = beta42 !=0. There is no significant effect of intervention group on the change in subject-specific odds of a more favorable response over the duration of the study.

#3.a. iv interpret the estimates for the intercepts when the response is nominal (the current model): for every one unit change in Xijk , the log-expected-count (or the log-expected-rate) will change by β for a ‘typical subject’, i.e., bi=0 for mean and median.

## 3v
#Delete duplicates
m1.pred.eta <- predict(m3.1, type="link", ranef=FALSE)
m1.pred.eta <- data.frame(unique(cbind(tx=data$Treatment, Month=data$Month, m1.pred.eta)))
#Reshape m1.pred.eta from wide to long
m1.pred.eta <- reshape(m1.pred.eta, varying=list(3:4), direction="long")


### Include the treatment differene in baseline
#Calculate subject-specific ratios of increased odds of a favorable outcome across time 
#in subjects randomized to anti-psychotic medication relative to subjects randomized to placebo
or1 <- m1.pred.eta[m1.pred.eta$tx==1,-5]
or <- cbind(or1, Eta0=m1.pred.eta[m1.pred.eta$tx==0,4])
or$logor <- or$Eta1 - or$Eta0
#Get odds ratios
or$or <- exp(or$logor)
#Create a factor variable
or$level <- factor(or$time)

#Plot estimated subject-specific baseline odds ratios over time (Drug vs Placebo)
p2 <- ggplot(or, aes(x=Month, y=or, group=level))
p2 + geom_line(aes(color=level)) + geom_point(aes(color=level)) +
  labs(title="Estimated Subject-Specific Baseline Odds Ratios over Time: Drug vs Placebo 
       (Including difference in baseline)", y="Odds Ratio")

Interpret the estimated odds ratios at 4 months of follow up for each specific equation:

Estimated ORt=4 = exp(β41sqrt(4))=exp(0.540732)=2.94898

At 4 months, a patient assigned to treatment is approximately 2.94898 times more likely to feel “Very Good” vs. “Very Poor” when compared to a similar patient treated with placebo.

Estimated ORt=4 = exp(β42sqrt(4))=exp(0.179892)=1.43301

At 4 months, a patient assigned to treatment is approximately 1.43301 times more likely to feel “Fair” vs. “Very Poor” when compared to a similar patient treated with placebo.
